06424nam a22009735i 9781487538927DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875389277 a10.3138/97814875389272doi  a(DE-B1597)650642  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ6351b.D73 2022 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a863/.322300aDrawing the Curtain :bCervantes's Theatrical Revelations /ced. by Adrienne L. Martín, Esther Fernández. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b6 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Iberic00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Poetics of the Imagined Stage -- tPART ONE Alternate Theatricalities in Cervantes’s Drama -- t1 Cervantes and the Simple Stage -- t2 Queer cambalaches in El rufián dichoso -- t3 Of Players and Wagers: The Theatricality of Gambling for Salvation in El rufián dichoso -- t4 Writing to Rescue from Oblivion: The Phantasms of Captivity in El trato de Argel -- t5 Captivating Music, Memory, and Emotions in Los baños de Argel -- t6 In the Name of Love: Cervantes’s Play on Captivity in La gran sultana -- t7 Revolving Sets: Spatial Revelations in the entremeses -- tPART TWO Acts of Disclosure in Cervantes’s Prose -- t8 Coups de théâtre in the Novelas ejemplares -- t9 Captive Audiences: Performing Captivity in Cervantes’s Prose Narrative -- t10 Painting into Theatre: “The Suicide of Lucretia” as a tableau vivant in El curioso impertinente -- t11 “Muchas y muy verdaderas señales”: The Theatrics of Truth and Sincerity of Fiction in La Galatea -- t12 Eavesdropping or Spying? Secret Places and Spaces in Don Quixote -- t13 Don Quixote and the Performance of Aging Masculinities in Early Modern Spain -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMiguel de Cervantes’s experimentation with theatricality is frequently tied to the notion of revelation and disclosure of hidden truths. Drawing the Curtain showcases the elements of theatricality that characterize Cervantes’s prose and analyses the ways in which he uses theatricality in his own literary production. Bringing together the works of well-known scholars, who draw from a variety of disciplines and theoretical approaches, this collection demonstrates how Cervantes exploits revelation and disclosure to create dynamic dramatic moments that surprise and engage observers and readers. Hewing closely to Peter Brook’s notion of the bare or empty stage, Esther Fernández and Adrienne L. Martín argue that Cervantes’s omnipresent concern with theatricality manifests not only in his drama but also in the myriad metatheatrical instances dispersed throughout his prose works. In doing so, Drawing the Curtain sheds light on the ways in which Cervantes forces his readers to engage with themes that are central to his life and works, including love, freedom, truth, confinement, and otherness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aRevelation in literature. 0aTheater in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aDon Quixote.  aMiguel de Cervantes.  aPeter Brook.  aRenaissance.  aSpanish drama.  adrama.  adramatic works.  aearly modern Spanish literature.  aempty space.  aentremeses.  aperformance.  aprose.  arevelations.  atheatre.  atheatricality.1 aBurningham, Bruce R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalderón, José R. Cartagena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomínguez, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4ht